      "id":"sport/blog/2013/oct/06/live-prix-de-larc-de-triomphe-2013",
      "sectionId":"sport",
      "sectionName":"Sport",
      "webPublicationDate":"2013-10-06T11:03:53Z",
      "webTitle":"Talking Horses: Prix de l'Arc de Triomphe day in daily horse racing blog",
      "webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/sport/blog/2013/oct/06/live-prix-de-larc-de-triomphe-2013",
      "apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/sport/blog/2013/oct/06/live-prix-de-larc-de-triomphe-2013",
      "fields":{
        "trailText":"<strong>Tony Paley and Greg Wood: </strong>All the highlights from the Longchamp meeting featuring Europe's premier horse race",
        "headline":"Talking Horses: Prix de l'Arc de Triomphe day in daily horse racing blog",
        "body":"<h2>3.55pm Magnificent Treve an Arc angel</h2><p></p><p>Treve demolished her rivals to run out a spectacular winner of the Qatar Prix de l'Arc de Triomphe at Longchamp. Trained by Criquette Head-Maarek, the three-year-old filly was due to be ridden by Frankie Dettori until he suffered a season-ending injury on Wednesday at Nottingham.</p><p></p><p>With Dettori sidelined, Thierry Jarnet stepped in for the ride and he never had a moment of worry as his mount powered clear of Japanese star Orfevre, who finished runner-up for the second successive year, and Intello in third.</p><p></p><p>Head-Maarek said: \"I want to say thank you to Frankie Dettori as he rode an amazing race on her in the Prix Vermeille. I said to save her for today and he did. \"A big kiss and thank you to Frankie, I am sorry he is not here today. She won so well, the way she won was incredible.</p><p></p><p>\"She got no cover and had to come on the outside the whole way.\" Referring to the draw, she said: \"When horses are that good numbers make no difference and the ground makes no difference.\"</p><p></p><p>She went on: \"The jockey said she was travelling so easily he just let her go. I'm so proud for papa (Alec Head) who bred her and for the Sheikh. When he bought her, he said 'I want you win an Arc', I said 'I cant promise but I'll do my best'.\"</p><p></p><p>Asked if it was the highlight of her career, she replied: \"Of course. To win with a filly is extra special.\"</p><p></p><p>Christophe Soumillon felt Orfevre had turned in a fine performance, but thought Treve was unstoppable on the day.</p><p></p><p>He said: \"This year he was feeling very well and I was confident. [But] with the weight [allowance] the older horses give to the three-year-olds it is quite difficult for them. We had a good run. I would have preferred to sit fifth or sixth with a stronger pace but I don't think Treve was beatable today. It's not my decision [if Orfevere will return next year], it's for the team to discuss. It is always difficult to think a horse can come back as a six-year-old but we will see.</p><p></p><p>\"I think he's a great champion but Treve was the top horse today.\" <strong>PA</strong></p><p></p><h2>2.55pm Dalkala proves an Opera star</h2><p></p><p>Dalkala just got up in final stride to beat Tasaday and win the Prix de l'Opera Longines at Longchamp.</p><p></p><p>Trained by Andre Fabre and running in the colours of Godolphin's French arm, Tasaday was ridden handily by Maxime Guyon before assuming the lead two furlongs out in the mile-and-a-quarter heat.</p><p></p><p>However, Christophe Soumillon was just getting into stride aboard Dalkala and she rattled home in the final furlong to peg back Tasaday and edge out the grey filly in a tight photo finish.</p><p></p><p>Dalkala prevailed by the narrowest of margins for the Aga Khan and trainer Alain de Royer-Dupre with Roger Charlton's British raider Thistle Bird running a fine race in third. <strong>PA</strong></p><p></p><h2>2.15pm Karakontie battles to Lagadare victory</h2><p></p><p>Karakontie dug deep to see off Spanish raider Noozhoh Canarias in the Qatar Prix Jean-Luc Lagardere at Longchamp.</p><p></p><p>Christophe Soumillon was positive from the off aboard Noozhoh Canarias, setting a good clip in front while Stephane Pasquier was content to sit in behind and get some cover as one or two of the field raced keenly.</p><p></p><p>Noozhoh Canarias was one of those to take an early hold but Soumillon anchored him in front and he still looked full of running at the head of the straight. The Jonathan Pease-trained Karakontie was primed to challenge in behind though and when Charm Spirit made his move down the outside, Pasquier also kicked with his mount assuming the lead. He appeared to get a touch close to Noozhoh Canarias just short of the line with Soumillon snatching up but the better horse emerged victorious.</p><p></p><p>The Richard Hannon-trained Barley Mow was barely sighted in the seven-furlong heat and finished out of the frame.</p><p></p><p>Pease said: \"We have always thought he was a nice horse and he has proved it today, although he did have to grind it out. He's a big horse and he still has a lot of scope.\"</p><p></p><p>Alan Cooper, racing manager for the Niarchos family, expects Karakontie to be tried in Classic company next year, possibly in the French 2000 Guineas. He said: \"He has won here twice, so you would imagine you would look at the Poulains, but it's too early to say and Stephane said he is better at a mile than seven furlongs. I would think he'll have a trial next season, and then go for a Classic somewhere.</p><p></p><p>\"He is qualified for the Breeders' Cup but Jonathan felt he's had a hard race today. He's a horse who can develop over the winter and the thought is to keep him for next year now. Stephane has had a difficult year but he has come right and won us two Group Ones.\"</p><p></p><p>Pasquier was suitable impressed, saying: \"He's a horse who I have always believed in and today was perfect with a good draw. My job was only to find my way out and he did it very easily.\" <strong>PA</strong></p><p></p><h2>1.45pm Indonesienne pulls off shock win in Boussac</h2><p></p><p>Indonesienne swooped late to spring a surprise in the Total Prix Marcel Boussac at Longchamp.</p><p></p><p>Lesstalk In Paris set out to make all in the hands of Ioritz Mendizabal and was still in front and travelling well at the top of the straight. Richard Hughes was poised to challenge in behind on British raider Sandiva but when Lesstalk In Paris kicked for home, she found little in response. Hughes switched out to challenge again in the middle of the track but Flavien Prat was flying down his outside on the Christophe Ferland-trained Indonesienne, who swallowed up Lesstalk In Paris only yards from the post and went on to claim a clear victory. Charlie Hills' Queen Catrine took third after she too delivered a late flourish while Sandiva could only plug on for seventh.</p><p></p><p>Ferland was gaining consolation after Chalnetta was disqualfied from first place in Saturday's Prix Royallieu. He said: \"It was disappointing yesterday with Chalnetta, but we are over that now and this is fantastic. \"We took a chance and it has worked. I knew she had great acceleration from her first race and she was able to show it.\"</p><p></p><p>Hills was delighted to see his filly make the frame on ground that he thought did not really suit. He said: \"The main thing is that she's shown us she stays a mile which opens up options for next year. \"We will give her a nice break but today's race was run on tacky ground and it turned into a bit of a slog.\"</p><p></p><p>Hughes felt Sandiva was thoroughly unsuited by the ground. He said of Richard Fahey's runner : \"The ground was very sticky and it didn't suit my filly at all. That was not her true running.\" <strong>PA</strong></p><p></p><h2>1.15pm Maarek triumphs in Prix de l'Abbaye</h2><p></p><p>Maarek finished with a flourish to snatch the glory in the Qatar Prix de l'Abbaye, the opening event on Arc day at Longchamp.</p><p></p><p>Trained by Barry Lalor in Ireland, jockey Declan McDonogh produced his mount between horses inside the final furlong to see off Catcall. Hamza and Jwala were in a photo-finish for third, with the former just prevailing.</p><p></p><p>Hamza was quick to break and raced up the rail, but Catcall looked a likely winner as he was primed on the heels of the leaders before kicking for home. Catcall took the lead inside the distance but McDonogh weaved his way through to edge in front. Maarek responded positively and pulled clear at the line to land a first Group One success.</p><p></p><p>McDonogh said: \"They went very fast, but he got a nice lead off the horse who was second. He's very game and he loves soft ground. They've done a great job with him, and he goes to Ascot (Qipco British Champions Sprint Stakes) now with a great chance.\"  <strong>PA</strong></p><p></p><h2>Today's best bets, by Greg Wood</h2><p></p><p>Treve, still unbeaten and representing the accumulated wisdom of four generations of the Head family, showed an exceptional turn of foot to run down Wild Coco in the Prix Vermeille last time out. He looks the best bet in today's Prix de l'Arc de Triomphe at Longchamp. Ruler Of The World, the Japanese Derby winner Kizuna, André Fabre's Intello and Flintshire, and the St Leger winner Leading Light are strong contenders from the Classic generation too.</p><p></p><p>With such a broad range of talent lined up against him, Orfevre is simply too short at around 2-1 with the British bookmakers, since he clearly has his quirks and will need to be delivered with split-second precision.</p><p></p><p>He is likely to be shorter still on the PMU meanwhile, though one possible angle for those who do fancy the favourite could be to back him for a place on the PMU, since the travelling Japanese punters seem to be very much win-only backers. Last year, Orfevre paid nearly 2-1 for finishing second, while Deep Impact, the subject of relentless Japanese support back in 2006, paid only fractionally less for a place than he would have done for a win.</p><p></p><p>Al Kazeem, who is 16-1 with the bookies and could go off at an even bigger price on the PMU, has the worst possible draw in 18, but he is the third-best horse in the field according to Timeform and still has the scope to find a little improvement for the step up to 12 furlongs on soft ground. At his current odds, he is certainly worth a small each-way interest, but for win-only purposes, it is sensible to stick with the three-year-olds, who have won 15 of the last 20 Arcs.</p><p></p><p>Flintshire is interesting at a double-figure price on the form of his win in the Grand Prix de Paris, and his fourth place in the Prix Niel last time is no reason to write him off since Fabre will have been thinking only of the Arc.</p><p></p><p>Yet the claims of Treve are simply too obvious to ignore. She heads the ratings after just four starts, showed startling acceleration to win the Vermeille and has been prepared solely with Sunday's race in mind by Criquette Head-Maarek, one of the finest trainers in the business. She gets a useful weight concession from the colts and older horses too, and though her high draw is not ideal, <strong>Treve (3.15)</strong> has the raw ability to overcome it and become the third filly in a row to win the Arc after Danedream and Solemia. Al Kazeem and Flintshire could be the ones to chase her home.</p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/419176532|2013-10-07T10:05:57Z|d4d664ff40d4720be276efd3e9dc8c18604b4145 -->",
