      "id":"sport/2013/oct/05/arc-treve-longchamp-orfevre",
      "sectionId":"sport",
      "sectionName":"Sport",
      "webPublicationDate":"2013-10-05T16:04:57Z",
      "webTitle":"Arc hope Treve to deny Japanese challenge at Longchamp",
      "webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/sport/2013/oct/05/arc-treve-longchamp-orfevre",
      "apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/sport/2013/oct/05/arc-treve-longchamp-orfevre",
      "fields":{
        "newspaperPageNumber":"14",
        "trailText":"Treve can strike for fillies and for France in the Prix de l'Arc de Triomphe at Longchamp",
        "headline":"Arc hope Treve to deny Japanese challenge at Longchamp",
        "body":"<p>The shape of the Prix de l'Arc de Triomphe changed significantly on Saturday morning when it emerged that Novellist, the second-favourite with most bookmakers, was suffering from a fever and had not travelled to Paris. It is a mark of the depth in this year's field here at Longchamp, however, that even in his absence, this promises to be one of the strongest and most competitive renewals in recent memory.</p><p>The first nine names in the betting for Sunday's race would all be perfectly plausible winners, and the fact that horses of the calibre of Ruler Of The World, this year's Derby winner, and Al Kazeem, who has taken three Group Ones already this season, are trading at up to 9-1 and 16-1 respectively demonstrates the quality of the field.</p><p>There is little doubt that Orfevre will start favourite, however, because there will be several thousand Japanese racing fans in attendance to swell the Longchamp PMU pool. Orfevre looked like the best horse in the race last year, and would probably have won with the benefit of a lower draw, as Christophe Soumillon was forced to come wide on the yawning expanse of Longchamp's home straight, and Orfevre sought the sanctuary of the far rail when he needed only to keep straight to win.</p><p>While he looked like the most talented horse in an average field last year, this is a much better race and the three-year-olds in particular appear significantly stronger than those Orfevre faced then.</p><p>Treve, still unbeaten and representing the accumulated wisdom of four generations of the Head family, showed an exceptional turn of foot to run down Wild Coco in the Prix Vermeille last time out. Ruler Of The World, the Japanese Derby winner Kizuna, André Fabre's Intello and Flintshire, and the St Leger winner Leading Light are strong contenders from the Classic generation too.</p><p>With such a broad range of talent lined up against him, Orfevre is simply too short at around 2-1 with the British bookmakers, since he clearly has his quirks and will need to be delivered with split-second precision.</p><p>He is likely to be shorter still on the PMU meanwhile, though one possible angle for those who do fancy the favourite could be to back him for a place on the PMU, since the travelling Japanese punters seem to be very much win-only backers. Last year, Orfevre paid nearly 2-1 for finishing second, while Deep Impact, the subject of relentless Japanese support back in 2006, paid only fractionally less for a place than he would have done for a win.</p><p>Al Kazeem, who is 16-1 with the bookies and could go off at an even bigger price on the PMU, has the worst possible draw in 18, but he is the third-best horse in the field according to Timeform and still has the scope to find a little improvement for the step up to 12 furlongs on soft ground. At his current odds, he is certainly worth a small each-way interest, but for win-only purposes, it is sensible to stick with the three-year-olds, who have won 15 of the last 20 Arcs.</p><p>Flintshire is interesting at a double-figure price on the form of his win in the Grand Prix de Paris, and his fourth place in the Prix Niel last time is no reason to write him off since Fabre will have been thinking only of the Arc.</p><p>Yet the claims of Treve are simply too obvious to ignore. She heads the ratings after just four starts, showed startling acceleration to win the Vermeille and has been prepared solely with Sunday's race in mind by Criquette Head-Maarek, one of the finest trainers in the business. She gets a useful weight concession from the colts and older horses too, and though her high draw is not ideal, <strong>Treve (3.15) </strong>has the raw ability to overcome it and become the third filly in a row to win the Arc after Danedream and Solemia. Al Kazeem and Flintshire could be the ones to chase her home.</p><p>Cirrus Des Aigles, who was second only to Frankel in the global ratings last year, is barred from the Arc because he is a gelding, but he has a valuable alternative target in the Qipco Champion Stakes at Ascot in a fortnight after an impressive success by a length and threequarters in the Group Two Prix Dollar at Longchamp on Saturday.</p><p>Corine Barande-Barbe's seven-year-old has struggled to find his best form in 2013, but having travelled well through the first mile as Planteur set a strong pace, he powered clear of the field in the straight under minimal encouragement from Christophe Soumillon.</p><p>Victor Chandler cut Cirrus Des Aigles to 7-2 (from 8-1) for the Champion Stakes. \"He was nearly at his best today, and he will be at his best on the 19th,\" Barande-Barbe remarked. \"I never doubted him.\"</p><h2>Greg Wood's Longchamp tips</h2><p><strong>12.45</strong> Dutch Masterpiece <strong>1.20</strong> Lesstalk In Paris<strong> 1.55</strong> Karakontie</p><p><strong>2.30</strong> Silasol <strong>3.15</strong> Treve <strong>4.40</strong> Gordon Lord Byron</p><p><strong>5.10</strong> Tac De Boistron</p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/419138476|2013-10-07T10:05:57Z|1aea2c220533ab0ac99bd889336513ed289a3ba8 -->",
