        "newspaperPageNumber":"12",
        "trailText":"The André Fabre-trained colt Intello has the perfect credentials for the Prix de l'Arc deTriomphe",
        "headline":"Intello can triumph in Sunday's Prix de l'Arc de Triomphe",
        "body":"<p>Wet weather and wide draws have made things difficult for a handful of the fancied runners in Sunday's Prix de l'Arc de Triomphe but not for <strong>Intello (3.15)</strong>, who can provide his masterful trainer, André Fabre, with an eighth success in the Longchamp race. The colt is 12-1, having been less than half that in high summer, but it is fashion rather than failure which has left him friendless.</p><p>Intello has been beaten only twice in eight runs, both times at a mile, short of his best. In the French 2,000 Guineas he was given an impossible draw in 17 but still stormed home and was pipped by only half a length; in August he was a close third to Moonlight Cloud in a hot Marois, with Declaration Of War and Dawn Approach behind him.</p><p>No one who fancied Intello for the Arc should ever have been put off by those performances, in which he showed more pace than can reasonably be expected from a middle-distance horse. The question is whether he will be truly top-class at a mile and a half on a soft surface, having a fair amount of speed in his pedigree.</p><p>But the portents are excellent, as he pulled nicely clear of the French Derby field and cruised around on soft ground to win his warm-up race a fortnight ago, at a distance two furlongs shy of the Arc's. He may have idled in front but he did not appear tired.</p><p>Could he have a better profile? Fabre-trained three-year-olds have won six Arcs and this one is by Galileo out of a Danehill mare, a match-up which seems to make the entire bloodstock industry drool. Aboard is Olivier Peslier, seeking an unprecedented fifth Arc success.</p><p>Orfevre is much better drawn than when going so close last year but odds of 5-2 make no appeal, considering how few recent Arcs have been won by horses previously beaten in the race. His fellow Japanese raider, Kizuna, is interesting but the form of his narrow win over Ruler Of The World may not be quite good enough.</p><p>The winner of three Group Ones on the bounce, Novellist was impressive in landing Ascot's King George by five lengths. But he struggled to score at 1-6 last time and the balance of his form is not all one could wish for in an Arc second-favourite.</p><p>Treve has been drawn unhelpfully wide for her first race against males but not quite so wide as Al Kazeem, on the outside of the entire field in 18. That is a great pity for his trainer, Roger Charlton, who rarely gets the necessary material to compete in the great middle-distance races and who wanted to use the past three months to build up to this race.</p><p>Al Kazeem's owner preferred to keep the horse busy, with the result that this seems rather an afterthought. It is not only stall 18 but also five high-quality Group One races in a row that Al Kazeem has to overcome and he will be a mighty beast if he can do it. At 20-1 Leading Light is a more attractive each-way option.</p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/419077814|2013-10-07T10:05:57Z|9e79c5ee678080165056338550a2b067443087c7 -->",
