      "id":"sport/2013/oct/04/criquette-head-maarek-prix-de-larc-de-triomphe",
      "sectionId":"sport",
      "sectionName":"Sport",
      "webPublicationDate":"2013-10-04T19:12:00Z",
      "webTitle":"Criquette Head-Maarek wants second Arc triumph with Treve",
      "webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/sport/2013/oct/04/criquette-head-maarek-prix-de-larc-de-triomphe",
      "apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/sport/2013/oct/04/criquette-head-maarek-prix-de-larc-de-triomphe",
      "fields":{
        "newspaperPageNumber":"12",
        "trailText":"<p>Criquette Head-Maarek is aiming to add to the illustrious Head family tradition in the Prix de l'Arc  de Triomphe with her runner Treve</p>",
        "headline":"Criquette Head-Maarek wants second Prix de l'Arc de Triomphe with Treve",
        "body":"<p>There are many famous and familiar names scattered around the post-war history of the Prix de l'Arc de Triomphe but only one seems to run through it like a watermark. For three generations since 1947, when Willie Head saddled Le Paillon to win only a few months after finishing second in the Champion Hurdle, the Heads from Chantilly and the Haras du Quesnay near Deauville have trained, owned, bred and ridden Arc winners, and now their time may have arrived again.</p><p>It is 32 years since Alec Head, William's son, sent out the filly Gold River to win European racing's most prestigious and glamorous event, two years after Criquette Head-Maarek, Alec's daughter, became the first, and so far only, woman to train the winner with Three Troikas, who was owned by her mother, Ghislaine, and ridden by her brother, Freddy. She was the last of Freddy's four successes on the first Sunday in October, after Bon Mot, San San and Ivanjica. Freddy's father trained Ivanjica. His grandfather saddled Bon Mot.</p><p>It is Criquette Head-Maarek who will attempt to continue the family tradition this weekend when she sends Treve, the unbeaten winner of the Prix Vermeille, to the Bois de Boulogne, 66 years after Willie Head did the same with Le Paillon.</p><p>Arc day is a special afternoon for all the many thousands of spectators from Europe and beyond who crowd into Longchamp racecourse every year but for a member of the Head family it is something more.</p><p>\"I'll never forget that race [when Three Troikas won in 1979],\" Head-Maarek said this week. \"I can still see it perfectly clearly. This time it is nearly the same because Papa [planned] the breeding and we bred her and raised her, except that there is no Freddy on top. We still have her mother [at Haras du Quesnay], a sister in training who is beautiful and will run in a few weeks, a yearling filly coming in and [Treve's] mother is in foal to Motivator [Treve's sire] again.</p><p>\"When I won the Arc with Three Troikas my father was still training and he had good horses and I could work with them. Treve has only been working with three-year-old fillies but 34 years ago it was some colts of my dad's and I went to the Arc very, very confident when Three Troikas ran.\"</p><p>In addition to being the first woman to train an Arc winner, Head-Maarek was also – officially at least – the first to send out an English Classic winner, when Ma Biche took the 1,000 Guineas in 1983. This year's renewal is one of the strongest of the last three decades but, as in 1979, Head-Maarek will arrive at Longchamp in a positive frame of mind.</p><p>\"I'm going to the Arc with confidence this year too,\" she says. \"<a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/sport/2013/oct/02/frankie-dettori-fractured-ankle\" title=\"\">Poor Frankie Dettori broke his ankle</a> and won't be able to ride, and it's a tough thing for a jockey to have a silly accident like that, but I've got Thierry Jarnet, who rode her [to win the French Oaks] before.</p><p>\"She is very well and physically she has put on weight and improved <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/sport/2013/sep/15/frankie-dettori-treve-longchamp-arc-trials\" title=\"\">since her prep race in the Vermeille.</a> She's been very lightly raced. This will be just her fifth race, so she hasn't been over-trained and everything that she's done she's done it so easily that the race doesn't take <sup></sup>anything out of her.</p><p>\"Now you have to see her against the three-year-old colts and the older horses.It's not the same. It will be more difficult but she's very well.\"</p><p>Treve drew stall 15 on Friday morning, towards the outside of the 18-strong field lined up on Sunday, and it is 10 years since the outstanding Dalakhani became the last horse to win the Arc from a double-figure stall. Jarnet will certainly need a little luck if they are to find their way to victory but Treve has already proved in the Vermeille that her jockey will have instant acceleration to draw up on when necessary.</p><p>\"Frankie was locked on the inside in the Vermeille but he didn't try to get out, he just waited until the gap came,\" Head-Maarek says.</p><p>\"He knew the filly had a tremendous turn of foot and that's where she's strong. She's got an incredible burst of speed, I've never trained a horse with the kind of acceleration which she can produce. I've had good fillies but like that, never.</p><p>\"Even Three Troikas, she was very good but she had a long acceleration. This one can go from zero to 100 like that, in two strides. She's got an incredible burst of speed.</p><p>\"She did it once [to get running room], and then she went on to catch [the leader] Wild Coco. Twice she accelerated and there's not many horses who are able to do those things.\"</p><p>The strongly supported Orfevre, who looked sure to become the first Japanese-trained Arc winner 12 months ago until he veered towards the rail in the closing stages, is likely to start favourite on Sunday, while Kizuna, the Japanese Derby winner, is also prominent in the betting. Runners from Germany, Britain and Ireland also hold realistic hopes of victory.</p><p>Their most dangerous opponent, though, is likely to be a filly from nearby Chantilly whose pedigree and preparation are the result of many decades of both human and equine excellence.</p><p>\"They say this year is a better Arc than the previous year but I'm not that  sure,\" Head-Maarek says. \"For me the Arc is always good. It's the best horses of every country which come and race. It's fun to be there. Where we'll finish I don't know but we will do our best and she will do her best. She will put on a good show.\"</p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/419079286|2013-10-07T10:05:57Z|0838d07356ab6e0f2dec6162879d504fd7afa571 -->",
