      "id":"sport/blog/2013/may/03/kentucky-derby-2013",
      "sectionId":"sport",
      "sectionName":"Sport",
      "webPublicationDate":"2013-05-03T12:00:00Z",
      "webTitle":"Kentucky Derby: who will win America's most famous race? | Daniel Ross",
      "webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/sport/blog/2013/may/03/kentucky-derby-2013",
      "apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/sport/blog/2013/may/03/kentucky-derby-2013",
      "fields":{
        "trailText":"<p><strong>Daniel Ross:</strong> The leading contenders have come to the fore. We look at those with the likeliest chances at Churchill Downs on Saturday</p>",
        "headline":"Kentucky Derby: who will win America's most famous race?",
        "body":"<p>There's something elemental about the Kentucky Derby that taps into the nation's psyche. Against the backdrop of Churchill Downs' iconic twin spires, the Derby is a race that stirs America's penchant for a ripping yarn in a theater of high-stakes drama. Every year, it seems, America's most recognizable race comes attached with a story gilt-edged for the headlines, good and bad.</p><p>Last year was the furore surrounding Doug O'Neill, trainer of the winner, I'll Have Another. Before I'll Have Another had time even to remove his garland of roses, <a href=\"http://www.nytimes.com/2012/05/11/sports/trainer-of-kentucky-derby-winner-has-a-troubled-record.html?pagewanted=all&amp;_r=0\">the attention was swiftly diverted to O'Neill's litany of drug offenses that have blighted his training career</a>. Barbaro's stunning win in 2006 was a story of brilliance marred by tragedy when he broke down in the Preakness Stakes, his next race. Stories mined from further back include Secretariat's win in 1973 that catapulted him to triple-crown immortality. The headlines surrounding this year's renewal seem sterile in comparison – to this point, at least.</p><p>Much of the news generated thus far by the 2013 Kentucky Derby surrounds the new qualification system, an overhaul of the old formula that rewarded graded-stakes earnings – earnings accrued at any point in a horse's career. Without going into great detail, the old system recognized a horse's whole career over more recent efforts. To put it bluntly, your Derby contender could go from Pegasus to pit pony between two and three, and still enjoy a Derby berth at the expense of a horse who had shown the same generational transformation, only in reverse – or so the thinking went.</p><p>The revamped system is an attempt to rectify that problem. Under its new guise, Derby hopefuls are given a 36-race window of opportunity to qualify. The top four finishers in those races are awarded points on a sliding scale. Special emphasis and more points are given to certain races run during a 10-week period between February 23 and April 27 in a what-have-you-done-for-me-lately kind of deal.</p><p>The new system, however, has its share of detractors. But one gets the impression that the machinery of the revamped formula is going to be tinkered with before the greater portion of leading racing figures are satisfied or appeased, albeit somewhat. But that's for the future.</p><p>This year, the experiment is over, and the leading contenders have come to the fore. Here's a look at the horses with the likeliest chances on Saturday.</p><h2>Verrazano</h2><p><strong>Trainer:</strong> Todd Pletcher</p><p><strong>Jockey:</strong> John Velazquez</p><p><strong>Post position:</strong> 14</p><p><strong>Wood Memorial win:</strong></p><p><em></em></p><p>If this year's Kentucky Derby were the World Poker Championships, trainer Todd Pletcher would be holding a royal flush. Chief among his cabal of Churchill contenders is Verrazano, whose resum&eacute; is an immaculate read of four wins from four starts. He's a smashing-looking colt with a pedigree smeared with Derby-winning DNA. His win last time out in the Wood Memorial at Aqueduct was in a race that has supplied four of the last 20 Derby winners. What is more, jockey John Velazquez picked Verrazano over Orb – a decision more indicative, however, of the Pletcher-Velazquez connection than anything else.</p><p>With so many ticks in so many boxes, one could understand if Verrazano<br />was being discussed in the same hallowed whispers reserved for potential mega-champs. But he's not. This is primarily due to his victory over Normandy Invasion in the Wood Memorial that was heavier on slog than superlatives. Verrazano should have dismissed the Wood field with disdain. He didn't. Afterwards, one couldn't help but feel cheated of a more authoritative display. There is also the question of experience. Throughout Verrazano's four-race career, he has avoided the hustle-and-bustle and mud splattering kick-back of a tightly packed field. He might take to it like a cat to napping – one would rather not wait until the big race to find out.</p><h2>Orb</h2><p><strong>Trainer:</strong> Shug McGaughey</p><p><strong>Jockey:</strong> Joel Rosario</p><p><strong>PP:</strong> 16</p><p><strong>Florida Derby:</strong> </p><p><em></em></p><p>John Velazquez's reject is Joel Rosario's gain. And Rosario is a jockey on fire right now. Trainer Shug McGaughey's colt has shown fine improvement since his maiden win at Aqueduct last November. Since then, he's added an allowance win and a rallying victory in the Grade II Fountain of Youth Stakes at Gulfstream Park to his gold-medal haul. Then came Orb's scene-stealing performance in the Florida Derby, a race that has proven a springboard to Derby success to no less than five horses in the last 20 years.</p><p>Sitting in midfield, Orb took the lead a furlong from home before stretching clear of Itsmyluckyday, the horse who had defeated Shanghai Bobby the time prior. A horse hardened at the grindstone of tough graded stakes action, Orb possesses many of the qualities necessary to win at Churchill – tactical speed and unflinching stamina perhaps being his most valuable. If one were searching for an Achilles heel, it would be his temperament. He's a nervous, free-sweating sort. It hasn't proven a barrier to success thus far – it might do during the cauldron of the big race preliminaries. He's shown an improved disposition with each run, however. And a bullet workout Monday—four furlongs in 47.89sec—shows that he's in fine nick. So much so, Orb's now looks likely to go off favorite Saturday.</p><h2>Revolutionary</h2><p><strong>Trainer:</strong> Todd Pletcher</p><p><strong>Jockey:</strong> Calvin Borel</p><p><strong>PP:</strong> 3</p><p><strong>Louisiana Derby:</strong></p><p><em></em></p><p>In Revolutionary, trainer Todd Pletcher has a worthy understudy to Verrazano. And like Orb, Revolutionary has been showing improved form all spring to suggest that, come Churchill Downs on Saturday, he'll be a potent force. He broke his maiden in December, after which he overcame a troubled trip in the Grade III Withers Stakes at Aqueduct in February. That day, he showed an Astaire-like fleet of foot that is satisfying to see in a potential Derby candidate. At Fair Grounds at the tail-end of March, he set out his Kentucky stall with a hard-fought win in the Grade II Louisiana Derby.</p><p>The last Derby winner to hail from the Louisiana showpiece was Grindstone, who needed every inch of the trip to prevail at Churchill in 1996. Revolutionary's win at Fair Grounds in 2013 showed similar stamina-laden attributes: after being headed a furlong from home, Revolutionary clawed back to overhaul Mylute on the wire. It was a gutsy win – guts by the bucket load is what is needed come Saturday. The form of the race is suspect, however. A neck defeat of Mylute leaves one wondering as opposed to won over: will Revolutionary improve enough to follow in Grindstone's rose petal strewn hoof-prints? A few eyebrows were raised when he only jogged Tuesday morning, but he's a light framed individual who needs only to be kept ticking over. One huge plus: his post position. Three-time Derby winning Jockey Calvin Borel has got his favored spot down by the rail in three.</p><h2>Goldencents</h2><p><strong>Trainer:</strong> Doug O'Neill</p><p><strong>Jockey:</strong> Kevin Krigger</p><p><strong>PP:</strong> 8</p><p><strong>Santa Anita Derby:</strong></p><p><em></em></p><p>The similarities between Goldencents and last year's Derby champ, I'll Have Another, are there in stark relief: Same trainer in Doug O'Neill, the same Derby prep victory in the Grade I Santa Anita Derby.</p><p>Goldencent's win at Santa Anita dispelled in one minute and 48 seconds the doubts hovering over him following his defeat in the San Felipe the time prior. That day, he was snared in a speed duel up front with Flashback, only to weaken close home, a spent force. Back at the Californian track a month later and the result was vastly different.</p><p>Ridden more conservatively, Goldencents prevailed in convincing fashion against his San Felipe nemesis, Flashback. But the form of the race – of the west coast form in general –&nbsp;leaves one questioning whether Goldencents has shown enough to gift O'Neill a double-whammy of Derby victories. As is usually the case, the best three-year-old form leading into the Derby has been the preserve of the east-coasters. But Goldencents' winning time at Santa Anita was good, and in a well-worn racing maxim: he can only beat what's put before him. He's settled in well at Churchill this week and the O'Neill camp are bullish on his chances.</p><h2>Overanalyze</h2><p><strong>Trainer:</strong> Todd Pletcher</p><p><strong>Jockey</strong>: Rafael Bejarano</p><p><strong>PP:</strong> 9</p><p><strong>Arkansas Derby:</strong> <br /><em></em></p><p>Another leading contender and another horse whose head hangs over the<br />webbings at the Todd Pletcher barn. Overanalyze's berth at Churchill<br />is due largely to a fine win in the Arkansas Derby at Oaklawn Park<br />last time out. That day, he angled wide around a large field before<br />being sent to the lead a furlong from home. Once there, he was<br />extended to romp clear by a visually impressive four and a quarter<br />lengths.</p><p>Given the paucity of top-notch competition that day, Overanalyze<br />needed to win in convincing fashion to achieve two things: to be taken<br />seriously as a Derby contender and to dispel the specter of his<br />lifeless performance in the Gotham Stakes the time prior. He did just<br />that. As an added plus, his works leading into the race have been<br />electric. But compared to his stable mates who have exhibited<br />stronger, more consistent, form, one has to exercise just a little<br />more imagination to see him claim gold on Saturday.</p><h2>Java's War</h2><p><strong>Trainer:</strong> Kenny McPeek</p><p><strong>Jockey:</strong> Julien Leparoux</p><p><strong>PP:</strong> 19</p><p><strong>Blue Grass Stakes:</strong></p><p><em></em></p><p>Up until the Blue Grass Stakes at Keeneland earlier this month, Java's<br />War had shown enough to suggest that he was a capable enough sort -<br />but a capable enough sort who lacked what was necessary to triumph at<br />Churchill. Three stake-race defeats were capped with a second place<br />finish in the Tampa Bay Derby to Verrazano. Trainer Kenny McPeek then sent Java's War to Keeneland.</p><p>In the Blue Grass, Java's War stumbled out of the gates, relegating<br />himself to the rear of the field for much of the way. There he<br />remained, the class dunce, until brought wide and set for home at the<br />top of the stretch. He soared, and nailed Palace Malice on the wire in<br />taking fashion. He didn't beat much that day – Palace Malice was<br />coming off a seventh place finish in the Louisiana Derby. It was the<br />manner of Java's War's victory, however, that suggests he's improved<br />considerably since the Tampa Bay Derby when Verrazano beat him by a<br />comfortable three lengths. Young horses in the spring are capable of<br />remarkable physical and mental maturation within a brief window of<br />time. It's quite possible that Java's War has matured enough give<br />Verrazano a much sterner test on Saturday. His wide draw over in 19 is<br /> a concern – it's a problem, but not an insurmountable one.</p><h2>Normandy Invasion</h2><p><strong>Trainer:</strong> Chad Brown</p><p><strong>Jockey:</strong> Javier Castellano</p><p><strong>PP:</strong> 5</p><p>Another of Verrazano's vanquished foes, Normandy Invasion, was the horse that gave Pletcher's star colt a tough time of it in the Wood Memorial. Prior to that race, Chad Brown's runner had shown only reasonable form in a couple of Grade Twos: the Risen Star Stakes at Fair Grounds and the Remsen Stakes at Aqueduct, neither of which suggested that Normandy Invasion was going to make Verrazano roll up his sleeves.</p><p>Like Java's War, one gets the impression that Normandy Invasion is on the up. Unlike Java's War, we haven't been privy to another racecourse appearance to be able to gauge by what degree he has improved. If he wins on Saturday, he joins Giacomo and Mine That Bird as horses that succeeded at Churchill after last-time-out defeats.</p><p><strong>Win:</strong> Orb</p><p><strong>Bigger priced outsider:</strong> Java's War</p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/408234988|2013-10-07T10:05:57Z|fb08b15f107276a2db956613d20bd02cef8c332f -->",
